                <p>
                    The JavaScript exercises displayed to the right are designed to showcase the flow of logic when trying to use, manipulate, and sort user input via strings and
                    arrays. Below is a description of each of the different JavaScript exercises provided during the Coder Foundry bootcamp.
                </p>
                <p>
                    PALINDROME: This exercise takes an input as a string, removes all special characters and spaces, reverses the string, then comares the reversed string to the 
                    original input. This is done without using .Reverse().
                </p>
                <p>
                    FIZZBUZZ: This is my favorite of the exercises. Here I take two number inputs of user choice. I then cycle through the numbers 1-100.  For every multiple of the 
                    lowest number, the number is replaced by "Fizz". Every multiple of the second number is replaced by "Buzz". Each number that is divisible by both numbers is 
                    replaced by "FizzBuzz". One intersting caviat that sparked some debate within my household, is what happens when one input is divisible by another. Let's use the 
                    numbers 3 and 6, for example.  Playing FizzBuzz should result in "1, 2, Fizz, 4, 5...". What happens at 6?  Well, it is divisible by 3, so it should get a "Fizz", 
                    but it's also divisible by 6, so it should get a "Buzz". It's also divisible by both numbers, which gives it a "FizzBuzz". It turns out, people have differing views 
                    on what the 'correct' replacement for 6 is.  In this exercise, I have decided to give it all 3!
                </p>
                <p>
                    MATH: Here I take any 5 number inputs of the user's choosing. Each number input is entered into an array, which I sort through to determine the greatest number, 
                    the lowest number, the mean of all of the numbers, the sum of all of the numbers, and the product of the 5 numbers.
                </p>
                <p>
                    FACTORIAL: This exercise determines the factorial value of the user's input.
                </p>
                <p>
                    ALPHABET ORDER: Here I take any string input and remove all special characters. I then sort the letters by alphabetical order.
                </p>
                <p>
                    COMBINATIONS: Here I applied a third-party program to produce all combinations of a string input.
                </p>
                <p>
                    PRIME NUMBER: This exercise uses more math to determine if the number input is a prime number or not. If it is not prime, it returns one value that it is divisible 
                    by.
                </p>
                <p>
                    UPPER CASE: This exercise takes any phrase and sorts through the string, and returns only the first letter of each word capitalized.
                </p>
                <p>
                    VOWEL COUNT: This exercise sorts through each letter of the user input and sorts out each vowel, returning a list of all vowels found and a total count. 'Y' does 
                    is not a vowel in this instance.
                </p>
